# Canonical list of Meshery's remote providers - the single source of truth for
# provider URLs across every install artifact (docker-compose files, the Helm chart,
# raw k8s manifests, the playground manifests, the docker-extension chooser, the UI
# deep-link constants, the e2e defaults, the mesheryctl fallback, and the server's
# viper default). Each line is `Name=URL`: Name is the human-friendly provider name
# (also a valid PROVIDER pre-selection value and the label shown in the extension
# chooser), URL is the provider's base URL.
#
# After editing, run `make generate-install` to propagate to all generated artifacts.
# `make check-install` (CI) fails if anything is out of sync.
#
# ACTIVE providers (uncommented lines below) are registered at server startup and
# emitted into PROVIDER_BASE_URLS. They MUST resolve in DNS: the server retries each
# unreachable provider URL 10x (3s apart) at startup, so an unreachable host adds ~30s
# before Meshery serves traffic and breaks the e2e/meshsync integration tests. The
# first active provider is the PRIMARY (used by single-URL consumers: the docker
# extension, playground, UI deep-links, provider-ui return-to, and e2e defaults).
Meshery=https://cloud.meshery.io
Layer5=https://cloud.layer5.io
#
# DECLARED-but-INACTIVE providers (the `#inactive ` lines below) are part of the
# canonical roster but are NOT registered, because their hostnames do not currently
# resolve in DNS - activating them would block startup behind retry timeouts. They are
# kept here so re-enabling is a one-line change: drop the `#inactive ` prefix and run
# `make generate-install` once the provider's DNS is live.
#inactive DigitalOcean=https://meshery.digitalocean.com
#inactive CleverLuck=https://idp.cleverluck.com
#inactive Exoscale=https://designer.exoscale.com
#inactive Intel=https://perf.platform.intel.com
#inactive UT Austin=https://ppf.research.utexas.edu
#inactive TCS Labs=https://tcs-labs.in
